to a practical subject, the

6
00:00:12,130 --> 00:00:14,260
subject of inference.

7
00:00:14,260 --> 00:00:17,030
The general idea is that we
have a probabilistic model

8
00:00:17,030 --> 00:00:19,400
involving several random
variables.

9
00:00:19,400 --> 00:00:21,740
We observe the values
of some of them.

10
00:00:21,740 --> 00:00:25,230
And we want to make inferences
on some of the others.

11
00:00:25,230 --> 00:00:28,340
Note that the unknown quantities
are modeled as

12
00:00:28,340 --> 00:00:31,020
random variables, which
means that we can

13
00:00:31,020 --> 00:00:32,299
use the Bayes rule.

14
00:00:32,299 --> 00:00:34,590
And so we will stay within
the realm of

15
00:00:34,590 --> 00:00:37,930
so-called Bayesian inference.

16
00:00:37,930 --> 00:00:41,070
In the four lectures that
follow, we will illustrate the

17
00:00:41,070 --> 00:00:44,040
use of the Bayes rule
in various settings.

18
00:00:44,040 --> 00:00:46,730
We will discuss different
methods of coming up with

19
00:00:46,730 --> 00:00:49,620
estimates of unobserved
random variables.

20
00:00:49,620 --> 00:00:51,670
And we will illustrate
the methodology

21
